ng <a href="/youngchampions/">Young Champions</a>, <a href="/revolution/">Middle School</a> and <a href="/z-the-2010-youth-summer-experience-calendar/" target="_self">High School</a> Activities, All-Church Picnic&nbsp;and more...</p>
<blockquote>We came across this great article by&nbsp;<a target="_blank" href="http://headandheartparent.com/contact-shelly-love-and-logic/">Shelly Moorman, founder of&nbsp;Head and Heart Parent</a>&nbsp;we thought was excellent:</blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>5 Steps to Sanity This Summer</h2>
<p>As much as I love the summer break I also stress thinking about &ldquo;What am I going to do with my kids this summer?&rdquo;&rdquo; How am I going to keep them busy and not zoning in front of TV or computer?&rdquo; &ldquo;When am I going to get things done?&rdquo; Instead of dreading summer, use these ideas for making this a great summer for you and your children!</p>
<h4>1. Hold a Family Meeting</h4>
<p>Let everyone share their views on what will make the summer a success. Make a list of chores and divide up responsibility among all family members so every feels like they are contributing and a valued member of the team. Children can contribute more in the summer since they don&rsquo;t have homework.</p>
<h4>2. Agree on Rules</h4>
<p>Family meetings are a good time to decide upon summer rules for &ldquo;screen time,&rdquo; reading, activities, play dates and more. Ask the kids what they think is reasonable and negotiate from there. One summer my 9 year old son volunteered the rule for 2 hours of screen time a day and you could earn more screen time for every hour you read. Since this was his idea, it was much easier to get his cooperation to comply all summer long and I was thrilled.</p>
<h4>3. Explore Your Options</h4>
<p>Look into what is available for your child in your community this summer and what would be fun for you?</p>
<ul class="list_002">
<li>Check out the Parks &amp; Recreation Centers for mini camps, outings, and sports.</li>
<li>Explore community water parks in your area and visit a different one each week. My favorites are in Littleton and Golden.</li>
<li>Google &ldquo;free factory tours&rdquo; and plan outings. My favorites are Hammond Candy and Celestial Seasonings.</li>
<li>Join multiple library systems summer reading programs and local bookstores. If your kids finish one program they can work on the next to keep them motivated to read all summer long.</li>
<li>Go on a hike! I&rsquo;m a huge fan of Jefferson County Open Spaces for kid friendly hikes within 30-45 minute drive. My favorite is Lair 0&rsquo;Bear for a stream to play in, easy hike, and great picnic spaces.</li>
</ul>
<h4>4. Structure Your Routine</h4>
<p>Decide what your family&rsquo;s general daily routine will be with set bedtimes, TV times, outdoor times, mealtimes, quiet times, whatever works for you. Routines can make a big difference in your child&rsquo;s behavior and your sanity.</p>
<h4>5. Make Time for Yourself</h4>
<p>Taking care of yourself and your marriage is vital if you are to have the resources for coping with the constant demands and stress of parenting.</p>
<ul class="list_002">
<li>Get up early and let your kids sleep late to find some quiet time.</li>
<li>Trade with another parent to watch kids so you can run errands.</li>
<li>Plan parent-child date so one parent take the children out every week giving the other parent a chance to relax with the house all to themselves.</li>
<li>Plan date night each week for you and your spouse to go out together without the children or for the children to go elsewhere while you two stay at home alone.</li>
</ul>
<p>Enjoy your summer!</p>||kids-out-of-school-worried-about-your-sanity-this-summer||||||||http://www.pcctoday.com/monkimage.php?mediaDirectory=mediafiles&mediaId=2211283&fileName=header--2013--experience-summer-50-50-0-0.jpg~~Pastor Ray Noah, &quot;What God has told me...&quot;||<img src="http://f049e6c6bc51d6086828-1f3d9bf827f6f62072870f1ea348709c.r40.cf2.rackcdn.com/uploaded/s/0e732651_staff-header--ray-noah--20091110.jpg" alt="" />||As I have prayed for our church and the great people of Portland Christian Center, God has spoke to me so clearly, &quot;It is time for the Church of Jesus Christ to wake up and prepare for ...||Ray Noah||May 24 2013||<h3>Wake Up: This Is Not Business As Usual</h3>
<p>As I have prayed for our church and the great people of Portland Christian Center, God has spoke to me so clearly, "It is time for the Church of Jesus Christ to wake up and prepare for action!" Friends, as we look at the world around us we can't help but notice our time here on earth is short and no longer can we have a business-as-usual approach to life. For certain, we face obstacles and opposition, but also the harvest is unusually ripe and the opportunities for kingdom advancement are great. <strong>And, the good news is for all we face here on earth, we have this certain promise that the future belongs to God&rsquo;s people&mdash;if we are prepared!</strong></p>
<hr />
<h4></h4>
<h4>You might be asking what does this mean for me?</h4>
<p>My job as your Lead Pastor is to prepare you! Through sermon series, midweek connection classes, Sunday morning groups/classes, special guests and outreach opportunities...you will see our focus in 2013 to prepare the church in these Four Calls to Action in 2013:</p>
<h3 style="padding-left: 30px;">1. &nbsp;Prepare for Christ&rsquo;s Return</h3>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;"><i>&ldquo;Wake up, for our salvation is nearer now than when we first believed.&rdquo;</i> ~Romans 13:11</p>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;">THE CALL:&nbsp; The signs are clear and the evidence is undeniable: The time for Christ&rsquo;s promised return is nearer than ever before.&nbsp; God is calling his church to prepare the Second Coming and to live ready to go in a moment&rsquo;s notice&mdash;which means living in such a way that we are investing in the things today that will matter in the light of eternity.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;"><a href="http://www.pcctoday.com/extras/sermons-download/">Check out the Sermon Series:&nbsp; I &amp; II Thessalonians, "In A Twinkling of An Eye" </a>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<h3 style="padding-left: 30px;">2. &nbsp;Prepare for a Coming Economic Earthquake</h3>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;"><i>&ldquo;Will not your debtors suddenly arise? Will they not wake up and make you tremble? Then you will become their victim.&rdquo;</i> ~Habakkuk 2:7<b><i></i></b></p>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;">THE CALL: There are an increasing number of prophetic voices warning of a coming economic collapse.&nbsp; Over the last few years, we have witnessed globally and felt personally the shakings of our long-trusted financial foundations. Now God is calling his people, individually and corporately, live by the financial principles of his Word&mdash;which means getting out and staying out of debt, honoring the storehouse principle and being free to invest in the things that matter in light of eternity.</p>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;"><a href="http://www.pcctoday.com/ministries/adult-education/">Check out Financial Peace, and the LifeSkills Class&nbsp;</a></p>
<h3 style="padding-left: 30px;">3. &nbsp;Prepare to Reach the World of Islam&nbsp;<a href="http://www.pcctoday.com/ministries/adult-education/"></a></h3>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;"><i>&ldquo;Wake up and look around. The fields are already ripe for harvest.&rdquo;</i> ~John 4:35</p>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;">THE CALL:&nbsp; God is stirring the hearts of Islamic people throughout the world.&nbsp; Through dreams, visions and the courageous witness of God&rsquo;s people, Muslims are coming to Christ by the thousands.&nbsp; Now God is calling our church to plant ant churches among Muslim background people&mdash;both abroad, and right here in Portland.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;">Check out the Midweek Connection in July for a special training series. And, our special guest on Sunday, July 28&nbsp;</p>
<h3 style="padding-left: 30px;">4. &nbsp;Prepare for Spiritual Warfare</h3>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;"><i>&ldquo;Be on your guard and stay awake. Your enemy, the devil, is like a roaring lion, sneaking around to find someone to attack. But you must resist the devil and stay strong in your faith.&rdquo;</i> ~I Peter 5:8-9</p>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;">THE CALL:&nbsp; God&rsquo;s Kingdom is advancing in unprecedented ways, but that doesn&rsquo;t means the god of this age will give up territory that he has long held without a fight.&nbsp; The voice of the Spirit is clear, and God&rsquo;s people step forward in faith to follow God&rsquo;s call, spiritual opposition and out-and-out warfare will increase. Now God is calling his people to prepare for war by learning the art of spiritual warfare&mdash;which means that we must become alert and armed for Satanic intrusion through demonic harassment, devilish pressure and outright persecution.</p>
<p style="padding-left: 60px;"><a href="http://www.pcctoday.com/services/">Check out our Summer Sermon Series: &nbsp;We Win! &nbsp;Fully Equipped for Spiritual Battle.</a></p>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>Want more? &nbsp;Join me for The Pastor's Circle on Wednesdays:</h3>
<p>There is only so much that can be said in a 30 minute sermon on a Sunday morning. When we consider the truths of the Second Coming of Christ, The End Times, and even the Spritual Warfare that seems to combat us, there is much to discuss! Click on the link below for more information on how you can join me in a small group setting to discuss in an intimate way our current series. It is here I will open up my research and sermon preparation to help you understand the complexity of these issues and how they impact you.</p>
<p><a href="/the-pastors-circle/" class="button">The Pastor's Circle</a></p>||pastor-ray-noah-what-god-has-told-me||||||||http://www.pcctoday.com/monkimage.php?mediaDirectory=mediafiles&mediaId=377357&fileName=staff-header--ray-noah--20091110-50-50-0-0.jpg~~Honoring an Outstanding Volunteer||<img src="http://f049e6c6bc51d6086828-1f3d9bf827f6f62072870f1ea348709c.r40.cf2.rackcdn.com/uploaded/h/0e735137_header--get-connected--children--home.jpg" alt="" />||Adventure Kids, the dynamic children's program of Portland Christian Center (Portland, Oregon) has been blessed with incredible volunteers who serve in so many ways in our active children's ...||||May 23 2013||<p>Adventure Kids, the dynamic children's program of Portland Christian Center (Portland, Oregon) has been blessed with incredible volunteers who serve in a variety of children's activities and programs within the children's department.</p><p>Last Sunday, we honored Wanda Baxter as our Adventure Kids Volunteer of the Month. Wanda has served in children's ministry for over 20 years! She has volunteered through all age groups, from rocking the littlest babies, to teaching our elementary children in Sunday School.&nbsp;The kids she once chased as preschoolers are now bringing their own kids to church for her to show God's unconditional love and care.</p><p><strong><em><img src="http://www.pcctoday.com/monkimage.php?mediaDirectory=mediafiles&amp;mediaId=2202023&amp;fileName=profile--volunteer--wanda-baxter-0-0-360-397.jpg" width="360" height="397" alt="Profile : Volunteer : Wanda Baxter" title="Profile : Volunteer : Wanda Baxter">Thank you, Wanda...</em></strong>&nbsp;for your faithfulness, for always being eager to serve where you are most needed, and for sharing so much love with the kids you work with every week. You are a blessing to the families of our great church, Portland Christian Center.</p><p><a href="/ministries/children/" class="button">About Adventure Kids</a></p><p><a href="http://www.pcctoday.com/ministries/children/serving-opportunities-with-children/" class="button">Ways You Can Serve!</a></p>||honoring-an-outstanding-volunteer||||||||http://www.pcctoday.com/monkimage.php?mediaDirectory=mediafiles&mediaId=393842&fileName=header--get-connected--children--home-50-50-0-0.jpg~~Planting Churches in Unreached Villages:  It is What We Do!||<img src="http://f049e6c6bc51d6086828-1f3d9bf827f6f62072870f1ea348709c.r40.cf2.rackcdn.com/uploaded/h/0e747843_header--care-and-serve--project-oromia.jpg" alt="" />||Portland Christian Center has planted over 800 churches in the last 3 years through the ministry of Petros Network.  What a tremendous accomplishment and one we are certain does not go unnoticed by ...||||May 19 2013||<p>Portland Christian Center has planted over 800 churches in the last 3 years through the ministry of Petros Network.&nbsp; What a tremendous accomplishment and one we are certain does not go unnoticed by God.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>As a church we have prayed a bold prayer, &ldquo;God, may we be the greatest conduit of the great commission the world has ever seen!&rdquo;&nbsp; We don&rsquo;t pray that prayer because we are arrogant or full of pride, but instead because our God is just that big!&nbsp; Why couldn&rsquo;t we be used that way?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><b>2 Chronicles 16:9</b> (NLT) says, <b>&ldquo;</b>The eyes of the Lord search the whole earth in order to strengthen those whose hearts are fully committed to him.&rdquo;</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Prayer:&nbsp;</strong> Our Heavenly Father, may we be a people committed to the things that you care about. Help us to see the world as you see the world. Help us to set aside our own desires for what you desire!<b></b></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="http://www.petrosnetwork.org" target="_blank">Learn more about the ministry of Petros Network &gt;&gt;</a></p>||planting-churches-in-unreached-villages-it-is-what-we-do||||||||http://www.pcctoday.com/monkimage.php?mediaDirectory=mediafiles&mediaId=671247&fileName=header--care-and-serve--project-oromia-50-50-0-0.jpg~~Pastor Ray Noah: I Am a Friend of God||<img src="http://f049e6c6bc51d6086828-1f3d9bf827f6f62072870f1ea348709c.r40.cf2.rackcdn.com/uploaded/s/0e732651_staff-header--ray-noah--20091110.jpg" alt="" />||Obviously, Abraham was a very special man, and the Bible holds him up as an example to emulate for believers like you and me. We all ought to be Abraham-like in the spiritual dimension of our lives. ...||Ray Noah||May 17 2013||<div id="verses">
<p class="scripture"><strong><strong>Together in 5<strong><strong>&times;</strong></strong>5&times;5 Bible Reading Plan</strong></strong></p>
<p class="scripture"><strong><strong>Read:&nbsp;</strong>Romans 4 <strong> Meditation: </strong>Romans 4:16<strong> </strong></strong></p>
<blockquote>&ldquo;God&rsquo;s promise of eternal life is received through the same kind of faith demonstrated by Abraham, who believed in the God who resurrects the dead and creates new things out of nothing.&rdquo;</blockquote>
</div>
<p><b>Shift Your Focus&hellip;</b> I don&rsquo;t know if you&rsquo;ve done much thinking about Abraham, but what a true hero of the faith! Here&rsquo;s a guy who was saved by faith even before there was a Bible or the Law or Christ&rsquo;s death and resurrection or a community of faith. God appeared to Abraham one day&mdash;we&rsquo;re not even sure if he&rsquo;d had any previous interaction with God or if this was simply an out of the blue encounter&mdash;and Abraham said, &ldquo;Okay God&mdash;I&rsquo;m on board. What&rsquo;s next?&rdquo;</p>
<p>Abraham then went on a life-long journey with God in which he became known as a friend of God&mdash;a pretty cool designation, I&rsquo;d say&mdash;the genetic father of God&rsquo;s people, the Jews, and the spiritual father of all who believe. (James 2:23, Romans 4:16-17)</p>
<p>Obviously, Abraham was a very special man, and the Bible holds him up as an example to emulate for believers like you and me. We all ought to be Abraham-like in the spiritual dimension of our lives.</p>
<p>But is that even possible? Is there even the smallest chance that I can develop that same kind of Abraham-like relationship with God? Can I attain a walk with God that will be an Abraham-like example to others? &nbsp;And if it&rsquo;s possible, then how?</p>
<p>Well, it is possible!&nbsp; Paul goes on to say, &ldquo;God will count us righteous too if we believe in him who raised from the dead this Jesus who died for our sins and was raised to make us right with God.&rdquo; &nbsp;(Romans 4:24, NLT)</p>
<p>How can we attain friendship with God?&nbsp; I can sum up the &ldquo;how&rdquo; in two words: Faith and hope&mdash;technically, that&rsquo;s three words, but work with me!</p>
<p><strong>First</strong>, you&rsquo;ve got to make resurrection the foundation of your faith.&nbsp;That&rsquo;s what Abraham did! Romans 4:17 says, &ldquo;Abraham believed in the God who brings back the dead to life.&rdquo; Abraham was a little ahead of his time&mdash;like a few thousand years&mdash;but he believed in the God of the resurrection. What Paul is referring to here is the story of God&rsquo;s call to Abraham to sacrifice his only son Isaac on the altar (you can read the story in Genesis 22), and Abraham&rsquo;s willingness to actually go through with it. Why would Abraham be willing to do such a thing? Because he had faith in the God of the resurrection&mdash;the God who could, and would, raise Isaac back to life again.</p>
<p>The truth is, to have that kind of Abraham-like faith, you and I have to have that same Abraham-like trust in the God of the resurrection. If you don&rsquo;t have a foundational and resolute belief in the resurrection of Jesus from the dead, and his promise to resurrect you from the dead, your faith will not only not develop to Abraham-like proportions, it will be meaningless. Paul teaches us in I Corinthians 15:14, &ldquo;If Christ is not risen, then our preaching is empty and your faith is also empty.&rdquo;</p>
<p>In other words, if we have no faith in the God of the resurrection, then I am wasting my energy writing this blog&hellip;and you&rsquo;re wasting your time reading it&hellip;and you&rsquo;ll never come close to living an Abraham-like life of faith. But the historical fact of the resurrection of Jesus from the dead proves that God is who he said he is and will fulfill what he has promised to do. And the faith you place in the God who resurrects the dead will empower you to live the kind of God-honoring faith that Abraham had.</p>
<p><strong>Second</strong>, you&rsquo;ve got to claim resurrection as the basis of your hope. That, too, is what Abraham did. Romans 4:18 tells us that &ldquo;even when there was no reason for hope, Abraham kept on hoping&rdquo;&hellip;believing in God&rsquo;s promises that one day he would be the father of many nations when his only son, through whom his lineage would continue, was about to die. In other words, Abraham didn&rsquo;t let his circumstances dominate his life; he allowed God&rsquo;s promises to dictate his life. Abraham believed that if Isaac was going to die on the altar, God would raise him to life. That was his hope.</p>
<p>I don&rsquo;t know if you&rsquo;ve ever thought about this, but the exercise of that kind of hope is arguably the most powerful discipline you can engage as a believer. Count Bismarck said, &ldquo;Without the hope of [Christian resurrection], this life is not worth the effort of getting dressed in the morning.&rdquo; He was right! Christian hope is that important, and that powerful.</p>
<p>Karl Marx proclaimed that religious hope is the opiate of the people. But Hebrews 6:19 says, &ldquo;We have this hope as an anchor of the soul, firm and secure.&rdquo; And Paul writes in Romans 5:5 that this &ldquo;hope does not disappoint us!&rdquo;</p>
<p>Do you practice hope? I&rsquo;m not talking about the breezy kind of optimism that Mary Martin sang about in South Pacific when she crooned, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m stuck like a dope with a thing called hope.&rdquo; I&rsquo;m talking about the exercise of hope that declares that you are choosing to believe in God&rsquo;s promises, not just in spite of the evidence, but in scorn of the consequences. We&rsquo;ve been called to practice that kind of hope.</p>
<p>Faith, hope and the resurrection&hellip;that was Abraham&rsquo;s secret. I have faith that it will be your secret too&hellip;at least I hope so!&nbsp; He is risen!</p>
<blockquote>&ldquo;For a mere legend about Christ&rsquo;s resurrection to have gained circulation and to have had the impact it had without one shred of basis in fact, is [unbelievable].&rdquo;<b> </b>~William F. Albright</blockquote>
<p><strong>Prayer...&nbsp;Thank you that by grace through faith, I am now your beloved child, a part of your forever family!</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p><a href="http://www.raynoah.com">For more posts by Pastor Ray Noah go to raynoah.com</a></p>
</blockquote>||pastor-ray-noah-i-am-a-friend-of-god||||||||http://www.pcctoday.com/monkimage.php?mediaDirectory=mediafiles&mediaId=377357&fileName=staff-header--ray-noah--20091110-50-50-0-0.jpg~~Pastor Ray Noah: Satan's #1 Strategy is Doubt ...||<img src="http://f049e6c6bc51d6086828-1f3d9bf827f6f62072870f1ea348709c.r40.cf2.rackcdn.com/uploaded/s/0e732651_staff-header--ray-noah--20091110.jpg" alt="" />||From the Word of God in general, from human experiencemine and other people Ive witnessed over the years, I could make a pretty strong case that doubt is the number one strategy Satan uses in ...||Ray Noah||Apr 10 2013||<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><b>Shift Your Focus&hellip;</b>From the Word of God in general, from human experience&mdash;mine and other people I&rsquo;ve witnessed over the years&mdash;and from this story in particular, I could make a pretty strong case that doubt is the number one strategy Satan uses in our lives to disrupt, weaken and ultimately destroy our faith in God.&nbsp; If he can get us to question the goodness and sufficiency of God and his Word, then our spirituality will be dead in the water.</p>
<hr />
<p class="highlight">EVERY TIME&nbsp;the devil came at Jesus with a temptation, the very first word was <strong><i>&ldquo;if&rdquo;</i> &mdash;<i>&ldquo;if you are the Son of God&hellip;if you will kneel and worship me&hellip;&rdquo; </i>&nbsp;(Matthew 4:3,5,9).</strong> Behind Satan&rsquo;s enticements was the goal of getting Jesus to question God&rsquo;s care and competence as well as his identity as the cherished Son of God.</p>
<hr />
<p>That is exactly what Satan will do to you&mdash;most likely even today.&nbsp; He will cause a question to arise in your mind as to the reliability of God&rsquo;s Word, the dependability of God&rsquo;s love, the sufficiency of God&rsquo;s supply, and the truthfulness of your unmovable place as a cherished child of God.&nbsp; Just like clockwork, the <strong><i>&ldquo;if&rdquo; </i></strong>question will be sown as a seed of doubt in your spirit before the day is out.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The number one defense against Satan&rsquo;s strategy to destroy your faith is trust&mdash;ruthless trust.&nbsp; Each occasion in which Jesus was hit with the big <strong><i>&ldquo;if&rdquo;</i></strong> was met with a return to what was unquestionable, unshakable and immovable&mdash;the Word of God.&nbsp; Jesus&rsquo; answer to the assault on his faith?&nbsp; <i>&ldquo;Scripture says&hellip;&rdquo;</i> (Matt. 4:4,7,10)&nbsp;</p>
<p>Jesus stood on the promises of Scripture, knowing that obedience to it was the only way to God&rsquo;s provision (<i>&ldquo;man shall not live by bread alone&rdquo;</i>), true spiritual muscle (<i>&ldquo;jump off&rdquo;</i> and prove your divine power), and ceaseless kingdom authority<i> </i>(<i>&ldquo;all the kingdoms of the world will be yours&rdquo;</i>).&nbsp;</p>
<hr />
<p class="highlight">Trust&mdash;ruthless trust. No assault from the enemy can penetrate it, and no temptation, regardless of the power of its enticement, can hold a candle against it.&nbsp; So no matter what, lean into God&rsquo;s Word today&mdash;there is nothing in all creation as reliable.&nbsp; Trust in God&rsquo;s character&mdash;his care and competence have never been proven impotent.&nbsp; Wait patiently for his provision&mdash;it will never lack the satisfaction you truly need.&nbsp;</p>
<hr />
<p>Analyze the things that are tempting you today.&nbsp; Find out how they assault your trust in the reliability of God&rsquo;s Word, the sufficiency of God&rsquo;s provision and the immutability of your position as a cherished child of God.&nbsp; Once you do that, you will see what temptation promises as nothing more than a false infinite&mdash;something that in the light of day cannot hold a candle to what God has in store for those who ruthlessly trust him.&nbsp;</p>
<p>By the way, when you respond to temptation with ruthless trust, not only do you punch Satan in the nose, but you give a priceless gift to God. I love what Brennan Manning says in his book, Ruthless Trust,</p>
<p><i></i><i>&ldquo;The splendor of a human heart which trusts that it is loved gives God more pleasure than Westminster Cathedral, the Sistine Chapel, Beethoven&rsquo;s Ninth Symphony, Van Gogh&rsquo;s Sunflowers, the sight of ten thousand butterflies in flight, or the scent of a million orchids in bloom.&nbsp; Trust is our gift back to God, and he finds it so enchanting that Jesus died for love of it.&rdquo;</i></p>
<p>So throughout the day today, look up, smile, and trust!</p>
<blockquote>Unwavering trust is a rare and precious thing because it often demands a degree of courage that borders on the heroic.&rdquo; ~Brennan Manning</blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>*Pastor Ray Noah is the Lead Pastor of Portland Christian Center and President of Petros Network. You can subscribe to his daily blog at <a href="http://www.raynoah.com">www.raynoah.com</a>.&nbsp;Portland Christian Center is a missional, life-giving church focused on bridging all ages and backgrounds to a loving God through faith in Jesus Christ.&nbsp;<a href="http://petrosnetwork.org" target="_blank">Petros Network</a> is non-profit organization focused on church planting and redemptive lift efforts. <a href="http://petrosnetwork.org" target="_blank">Petros Network</a> is responsible for developing leaders and planting thousands of churches in Ethiopia, South Sudan, and Uganda and providing compassionate care to the desperately poor.</p>||pastor-ray-noah-satans-1-strategy-is-doubt-||||||||http://www.pcctoday.com/monkimage.php?mediaDirectory=mediafiles&mediaId=377357&fileName=staff-header--ray-noah--20091110-50-50-0-0.jpg~~A Personal Story: Giving Up Offenses by Crystal J. Ortmann||<img src="http://f049e6c6bc51d6086828-1f3d9bf827f6f62072870f1ea348709c.r40.cf2.rackcdn.com/uploaded/h/0e735397_header--life-learning--lifeskills.jpg" alt="" />||Jesus said, It is impossible that no offenses should come, but woe to him through whom they do come!  Luke 17:1. The word offense in the New Testament comes from the Greek word ...||||Apr 01 2013||<div id="profile"><p class="name">Pastor:<br>Linda Noah</p><img src="http://www.pcctoday.com/monkimage.php?mediaDirectory=mediafiles&amp;mediaId=2091227&amp;fileName=profile--lindanoahwebinsert-0-0-143-200.jpg" width="143" height="200" alt="Profile : LindaNoah_webinsert" title="Profile : LindaNoah_webinsert">Crystal J. Ortmann ("Cris" to the Portland Christian Center Family) recently sent me her testimony about how God has been working in her life through our recent <em>Bait of Satan</em> Series in the LifeSkills Class. LifeSkills meets every Sunday simultaneous with the 9:00 AM church service where Cris, and her husband Frank, have been faithful participants. I love watching how each Life Learning series bridges people to a deeper walk of faith and becoming more like Christ each day. You too can join us Sundays at 9:00 AM in the gymnasium. LifeSkills is one of the Life Learning opportunities at Portland Christian Center. <a href="/adult-ministry-lifelearning--redirect/" target="_blank">(see Life Learning opportunities)</a> We always have room for one more! By the way...Cris is a wonderful and thoughtful author. You can pick up her recent release by click here &gt;&gt; &nbsp;<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1449776426/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1449776426&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=portlchriscen-20">From a Cry of Anguish to a Shout of Praise: Poetry and Prose for the Hard Times in Life</a><img src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=portlchriscen-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=1449776426" width="1" height="1" border="0" alt="" style="border: none !important; margin: 0px !important;"></div><p>&nbsp;</p><blockquote>Crystal J. Ortman is a wonderful and thoughtful author. You can pick up her most recent release here &gt;&gt; &nbsp;<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1449776426/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1449776426&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=portlchriscen-20">From a Cry of Anguish to a Shout of Praise: Poetry and Prose for the Hard Times in Life</a><img src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=portlchriscen-20&amp;l=as2&amp;o=1&amp;a=1449776426" width="1" height="1" border="0" alt="" style="border: none !important; margin: 0px !important;"></blockquote><h3></h3><div><p><em>&ldquo;&hellip;It is impossible that no offenses should come, but woe to him through whom they do come!&rdquo; &ndash; Luke 17:1</em></p></div><h3>GIVING UP OFFENSES</h3><p><strong>by Crystal J. Ortmann</strong></p><p>The new neighbors did not look very nice. In fact, I was repelled. I was also alarmed as they unloaded dog and cat.&nbsp; We feed birds and there is a &ldquo;no free-running cats&rdquo; rule in our apartment complex.&nbsp; The new neighbor didn&rsquo;t care.&nbsp; She said her cat wasn&rsquo;t used to being indoors.&nbsp; There was an instant clash of personalities.&nbsp; You know how it is when you first meet someone and you dislike them on sight?&nbsp; That&rsquo;s how it was.&nbsp; I also sensed darkness there.</p><p>I prayed they wouldn&rsquo;t last long, since the neighbors below us seem to be almost on a revolving door situation with many move-ins and outs.&nbsp; Before any time passed, the dog&mdash;a small one with a shrill bark (right under my office window) became a terrible annoyance.&nbsp; In fact, I had to try to drown it out with earmuffs, radio (I usually work with no noise) and a fan.&nbsp; It got so that when I heard the first bark, I jolted upright and my stomach tightened.&nbsp; I admit I got angry and frustrated.&nbsp; I didn&rsquo;t want to go to the manager, because the dog was just doing what dogs do, but the irritation persisted and got worse.</p><p>I tried being a little friendly with the people, but the woman was very abrasive and it seemed like every attempt met with some sort of disagreement.&nbsp; I prayed fervently that they would move soon.&nbsp; She also told me she was involved with some sort of New Age thing, which would explain the darkness I felt.&nbsp; I decided to ignore the situation and continued to pray for a quick removal of them from my life.&nbsp; My attitude was less than &ldquo;Christian.&rdquo;&nbsp; I knew it, but didn&rsquo;t seem to be able to change it, even when I prayed for them.&nbsp; I just felt irritated each time I saw them.</p><p><strong>At that time, we were studying about offenses in our Sunday school class.</strong>&nbsp; I honestly was offended by these people and though normally outgoing, I shrunk from any contact with them.&nbsp; I almost sneered when I thought about them.&nbsp; Through the study, I felt a nudging about truly praying for them with an open heart.&nbsp; &ldquo;Nope, not me.&nbsp; Just move &lsquo;em out, Lord.&nbsp; That will work for me.&rdquo;&nbsp; My attitude was atrocious, but I couldn&rsquo;t seem to force anything else out of myself.</p><p>In the past, God had this interesting way of putting people in my life who drove me up a wall.&nbsp; The more they did so, the more they seemed to be in my life.&nbsp; If I tried to avoid them, somehow they chose me to sit next to, or they wanted to talk to me.&nbsp; Only after fighting it and deciding to pray seriously for them, did I find any peace.&nbsp; This happened over and over and although we didn&rsquo;t become best friends, at least I could tolerate them (big of me, right?).</p><p>Still, this neighbor was something else.&nbsp; I mean, I had to see her many times in the day, if not in person, at least from my window.&nbsp; My sense of revulsion grew.&nbsp; I wrestled with God over this issue.&nbsp; The dog got nastier and even tried to snap at me once, which didn&rsquo;t endear her to me&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; at all.&nbsp; My sense of being put-upon rose.</p><p>&ldquo;Why me, God?&nbsp; Why is it always me?&nbsp; I just enjoy peace and I get along with all the other neighbors.&nbsp; Why me?&rdquo; I whined.&nbsp;</p><p>One day, I realized that the man was no longer there.&nbsp; I had heard he had lost his job, so I assumed he found a job somewhere else temporarily.&nbsp; After months, I asked her and she said he had left her and they had divorced.&nbsp; She was trying to find work but it was difficult.&nbsp; To my shame, I thought, &ldquo;Oh, yay.&nbsp; She won&rsquo;t be able to afford this apartment and will be out of here in no time.&rdquo;</p><p>Bit by bit, as I prayed, I thought I should be feeling some compassion, not just looking out for my own interests.&nbsp; I am normally a very compassionate person, so this in itself was surprising that I didn&rsquo;t feel any.&nbsp; I am also not a selfish person.&nbsp; My shame grew, yet I felt helpless to change my feelings and reach out to her.</p><p>The day before Christmas, I decided to write a short Christmas card and stick it through her mail slot. I could do that without having to talk to her.&nbsp; I saw her the day after Christmas, and asked her how she was.&nbsp; To my surprise, she told me it was the worst Christmas in her life.&nbsp; She said my card was the only card she got and it was the first Christmas without any gifts.&nbsp; Tears welled in her eyes.</p><p>I felt the first twinges of pity.&nbsp; I could identify with her feelings.&nbsp; We parted company and I had a thought.&nbsp; I had an extra stocking and my book <i>From a Cry of Anguish to a Shout of Praise </i>had just been published.&nbsp; It is a book for people going through hard times.&nbsp; She was going through hard times.&nbsp; I stuffed the book into the fleece-like stocking and took it down to her.&nbsp; I actually rang the doorbell.&nbsp; She came to the door, and I told her: &ldquo;No one should go through Christmas without a gift.&rdquo;&nbsp; Her face turned beet-red and her eyes overflowed.&nbsp; I wanted to hug her but the dog was in her arms and growling at me.&nbsp; I backed off quickly.</p><p>I didn&rsquo;t know if she would read it or even liked that sort of thing.&nbsp; I hoped and prayed she would find her way to the Truth through it.</p><p>Yesterday, she stopped me outside and said that the poem, <i>Sea of Agony</i> is what got her through the Christmas season.&nbsp; She said she tells everyone she is fine and acts like she has it together, but she admitted she is anything but fine.&nbsp; This truly blessed me because this is the purpose of the book.&nbsp; We talked and I actually found myself liking her.&nbsp; Even the dog let me near without barking.&nbsp; I feel certain that she will find her way to God.&nbsp; I even don&rsquo;t care if she stays living here. In fact, suddenly I started seeing many things about her that were positive.</p><p>This is not a testimony about her changing. It&rsquo;s a testimony about how a 40 year veteran in the Christian faith, who walks closely with the Lord, and who is normally compassionate and loving, can become offended by someone.&nbsp; Hanging onto that offense causes a cancer of dislike and hatefulness to grow.&nbsp; Letting go of it and watching God work, as well as confessing my selfishness and hateful attitude has been a good reminder that no matter how long I am a Christian, I still need Christ to show me my faults and to help me overcome them.&nbsp; I became obedient to Him (although kicking and screaming as I did so), and He forgave me and blessed me with a new friend and a potential sister-in-Christ.&nbsp; I give Him praise.</p><hr><p>&nbsp;Pick up a copy of Cry of Anguish to a Shout of Joy:</p><p><iframe width="320" height="240" style="width: 120px; height: 240px;" src="http://rcm.amazon.com/e/cm?lt1=_blank&amp;bc1=FFFFFF&amp;IS1=1&amp;bg1=FFFFFF&amp;fc1=000000&amp;lc1=0000FF&amp;t=portlchriscen-20&amp;o=1&amp;p=8&amp;l=as1&amp;m=amazon&amp;f=ifr&amp;ref=qf_sp_asin_til&amp;asins=1449776426" scrolling="no" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" frameborder="0"></iframe></p><hr>||a-personal-story-giving-up-offenses-by-crystal-j-ortmann||||||||http://www.pcctoday.com/monkimage.php?mediaDirectory=mediafiles&mediaId=394168&fileName=header--life-learning--lifeskills-50-50-0-0.jpg~~Join Our Family for Easter Sunday Church Services at 9:00 &amp; 10:45 AM||<img src="http://f049e6c6bc51d6086828-1f3d9bf827f6f62072870f1ea348709c.r40.cf2.rackcdn.com/uploaded/h/0e770397_header--easter-2013.jpg" alt="" />||Celebrate Easter Sunday with us and discover God's love for you at Portland Christian Center, a local SW Portland church. On Sunday, March 31, at our 9:00 &amp; 10:45 AM services, expect some great ...||PCC Communications Team||Mar 13 2013||<h5 style="margin-bottom: 15px;">Sunday, March 31, 2013 at 9:00 &amp; 10:45 AM</h5>
